"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior thyroid artery\u003C/strong\u003E (Image) is the first branch of the external carotid artery, arising from its anterior surface just below the level of the greater cornu of the hyoid bone. It supplies the thyroid gland and adjacent muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other branches arise in the following order:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eascending pharyngeal artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the posterior aspect of the external carotid near its origin. It provides three branches that contribute to the blood supply of the pharynx, the prevertebral muscles, the middle ear and the dura mater\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elingual artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises above the superior thyroid artery and supplies the tongue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises above the lingual artery and supplies the face\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the posterior surface of the external carotid artery and supplies the posterior scalp\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe external carotid artery terminates by dividing into the superficial temporal and maxillary arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior thyroid artery originates from the anterior surface of the external carotid artery inferior to the hyoid bone.","The ascending pharyngeal artery is the only branch arising from the posterior aspect near the origin of the external carotid artery.","The external carotid artery divides into the superficial temporal and maxillary arteries at its termination."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin 